What is a Regular Expression (Regex)?

A Regular Expression (regex) is a sequence of characters that defines a search pattern. It is commonly used for string matching, validation, searching, and replacement.

In PHP, regular expressions can be used with functions like:

preg_match() – Match a pattern

preg_match_all() – Match all occurrences

preg_replace() – Replace based on pattern

preg_split() – Split a string using a pattern
<?php

// 1. Check if a string contains digits
$input = "Welcome123";
if (preg_match('/\d+/', $input)) {
    echo "1. The string contains digits.\n";
}

// 2. Validate an email address
$email = "user@example.com";
if (preg_match('/^[\w\.-]+@[\w\.-]+\.\w+$/', $email)) {
    echo "2. '$email' is a valid email address.\n";
}

// 3. Replace all digits with '*'
$text = "Phone: 9876543210";
$replaced = preg_replace('/\d/', '*', $text);
echo "3. After replacing digits: $replaced\n";

// 4. Split a string by comma and/or whitespace
$data = "apple, banana orange";
$parts = preg_split('/[\s,]+/', $data);
echo "4. Split result: ";
print_r($parts);

// 5. Extract all words that start with capital letters
$sentence = "Hello World, this is PHP Regex.";
preg_match_all('/\b[A-Z][a-z]*\b/', $sentence, $matches);
echo "5. Words starting with capital letters: ";
print_r($matches[0]);

?>

